---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "How much stored energy is actually in a garage door torsion spring?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A double-car residential torsion spring on a standard 2.4m-high sectional is wound to roughly 7–9 full turns, which equates to 200–400 newton-metres of stored torque. That is enough force to break a forearm or shatter fingers if a winding bar slips. The spring does not care that you only intended to do a 30-minute job — once it lets go, it lets go in under a tenth of a second. This is why the trade uses specifically designed winding bars (not screwdrivers, not a length of rebar) and why every reputable installer cables the door to the track before the wind-up. We replace torsion springs across Cranbourne, Cranbourne East, West, North, South, Hampton Park, Junction Village, Botanic Ridge, Clyde and Clyde North every week, and the safety drill is non-negotiable on every single one." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Will my home insurance pay out if I'm injured doing a DIY spring repair?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Almost never. Standard Australian home and contents policies exclude injuries caused by unlicensed work on building components, and ambulance / hospital cover treats a spring strike as a domestic accident — you carry the cost. Worse, if the door subsequently fails on a family member, an insurer will often deny the building claim on the grounds the repair was performed outside trade standards. A $300 spring job done by us is a fraction of a single ambulance call-out fee, let alone surgery. We carry $20 million public liability and full workers' insurance — if anything goes wrong on our end, you are covered." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "How quickly can you get to a broken-spring call-out in Cranbourne?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Same-day if you call before 2pm Monday to Saturday, anywhere in the Casey inner ring — Cranbourne CBD, Cranbourne East, West, North and South, Hampton Park, Junction Village, Botanic Ridge, Clyde and Clyde North. We carry the four most common torsion spring sizes (riding diameter 2 inch, wire gauges .225, .234, .243 and .250) plus the standard extension spring pairs for older tilt and sectional doors. Roughly 85% of broken-spring jobs are fixed on the first visit. After-hours emergency call-out is available for stuck-door situations where a car is trapped inside or the property is exposed." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "Can I tell what type of spring I have from a photo before you arrive?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes — send a photo to quotes@cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au and we'll identify the spring system in under an hour. Torsion springs sit horizontally on a shaft above the door opening, usually one or two springs side-by-side. Extension springs run along the top of the tracks either side of the door, with safety cables threaded through them. Tilt-door springs are at the back of the garage and are a different beast entirely. Photo identification means we arrive with the right spring on the first visit — no second trip, no second call-out fee." }},
    { "@type": "Question", "name": "What does a proper spring replacement cost in Cranbourne in 2026?", "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "$250–$550 supplied and fitted on a standard single torsion spring, $400–$800 on a dual-spring setup, $200–$400 on a pair of extension springs. We upgrade builder-grade 10,000-cycle springs to 25,000-cycle commercial-grade as a standard inclusion — same install time, roughly $40 more in parts, and the next failure is pushed out from 7 years to 15-plus. Anyone quoting a flat $150 'all-in' on a torsion job is either fitting a 5,000-cycle import spring or skipping the cable replacement at the same time. Ask what cycle-rating the spring is — the answer should be a specific number." }}
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Garage Door Spring Tension Safety in Cranbourne — Why DIY Is a Hospital Trip | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Why torsion-spring repair on a Cranbourne garage door is a hospital-trip risk if DIY'd, the insurance coverage trap, our same-day spring failure response, and how to identify spring type by photo."
  canonical="https://cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au/spring-tension-safety-cranbourne/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Safety briefing — Cranbourne &amp; City of Casey</span>
      <h1>Garage door spring tension safety in <span class="accent">Cranbourne</span> — please, don&rsquo;t DIY this one.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        A wound torsion spring holds 200&ndash;400 newton-metres of stored
        energy. If it lets go during a DIY swap, it lets go in under a tenth of
        a second &mdash; usually into a forearm, a wrist, or the side of a
        face. Same-day spring replacement across Cranbourne, Hampton Park,
        Junction Village, Botanic Ridge, Clyde and Clyde North. $250&ndash;$550
        fitted, commercial-grade upgrade included.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Send a quote request</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The physics most homeowners don&rsquo;t know.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          A garage door spring isn&rsquo;t a spring in the household sense.
          It&rsquo;s an energy-storage device, sized so that when the door is
          closed it stores enough torque to counterbalance the entire dead
          weight of the door panels &mdash; typically 80&ndash;120 kg on a
          double-car sectional. That energy doesn&rsquo;t politely dissipate
          when something goes wrong. If a winding bar slips out of the spring
          cone during a wind-up, the spring unwinds completely in roughly 70
          milliseconds. That&rsquo;s faster than you can flinch.
        </p>
        <p>
          The standard a torsion spring is wound to is roughly 7&ndash;9
          quarter-turns past zero, which puts it in the 200&ndash;400
          newton-metre band depending on door weight. For comparison, a
          plumber&rsquo;s pipe wrench torquing a stuck fitting at full effort
          tops out around 150 newton-metres. The garage spring above your head
          right now is storing more than twice that &mdash; concentrated on a
          point you can&rsquo;t see and can&rsquo;t hear coming.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why the lifecycle matters.</h3>
        <p>
          Builder-grade torsion springs in new Cranbourne estates (Clyde North,
          Botanic Ridge, the newer Cranbourne East subdivisions) are rated to
          roughly 10,000 cycles. One cycle is one full open-and-close. A family
          doing the school run, sport pickup, after-work shopping and the
          weekend hardware run is comfortably hitting 5&ndash;7 cycles a day,
          which puts the spring at end-of-life in 5&ndash;7 years. We see this
          constantly: estates that were turned over in 2018&ndash;2019 are
          coming up for first-spring-failure right now, in 2026.
        </p>
        <p>
          When we replace, we standardise on 25,000-cycle commercial-grade
          springs. The install time is identical, the parts cost is about $40
          higher, and the next failure window moves out to 15&ndash;18 years.
          The maths is so plain that we&rsquo;ve made it a standard inclusion
          rather than an upsell &mdash; if you proceed with a spring job
          through us, you&rsquo;re getting commercial-grade unless you
          specifically ask for the cheaper part.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>The four ways DIY spring jobs go to hospital.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Wrong tooling:</strong> using a screwdriver or length of rebar instead of correctly-sized winding bars. The bar slips out of the cone, the spring unwinds, the bar becomes a projectile.</li>
          <li><strong>No safety cables on extension springs:</strong> the cable is the difference between a snapped spring whipping along the track and a snapped spring contained by the cable. New construction often has them; older Hampton Park and Cranbourne West homes from the 1980s&ndash;90s frequently don&rsquo;t.</li>
          <li><strong>Door not secured to the track:</strong> when you unwind a torsion spring, the door wants to fall. If it&rsquo;s not C-clamped to the vertical track on both sides, it drops on whoever is underneath.</li>
          <li><strong>Working alone:</strong> if something does go wrong, there&rsquo;s no one to call an ambulance or apply pressure to the wound. We always work in pairs on spring jobs for exactly this reason.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Identify your spring type before we arrive.</h3>
        <p>
          Send a photo of the area directly above the closed door to
          <a href="mailto:quotes@cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au">quotes@cranbournegaragedoorco.com.au</a>
          and we&rsquo;ll tell you which spring system you have before we leave
          the depot. <strong>Torsion springs</strong> are horizontal, mounted
          on a shaft above the door opening &mdash; one spring on a single-car
          door, two on a double-car. <strong>Extension springs</strong> run
          along the horizontal section of the track on each side, stretched
          when the door is closed. <strong>Tilt-door springs</strong> are at
          the rear corners of the garage, usually on older Cranbourne CBD and
          Hampton Park homes from before sectional doors became standard in
          the late 1990s.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Common questions about spring repair safety.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>How long does a professional spring replacement actually take?</h3>
        <p>
          30&ndash;60 minutes on a standard single-spring residential door,
          60&ndash;90 minutes on a dual-spring setup or if the cables need
          replacing at the same time (which is often &mdash; cables fray during
          the period the door was operated with a broken spring). We diagnose,
          quote and complete on the same visit in 90%-plus of cases.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Should I replace both springs at the same time on a dual-spring door?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes. The springs were installed together, have done the same number
          of cycles, and have aged in the same conditions. Replacing one and
          leaving the other is a guaranteed return call-out within 12 months.
          A dual replacement is roughly $400&ndash;$800 fitted &mdash; less
          than two separate single jobs.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">What if my door is still working but the spring looks rusty or stretched?</h3>
        <p>
          Visible rust along the coil isn&rsquo;t cosmetic &mdash; it&rsquo;s
          a stress riser, and that&rsquo;s where the spring will fail. If you
          can see a gap that wasn&rsquo;t there before, the spring is already
          partially failed. Stop using the door and call us. Continuing to
          operate strips the opener gear and can bend panels, turning a $300
          job into a $1,500 job.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Are your spring jobs compliant with AS/NZS 60335.2.95?</h3>
        <p>
          Yes. AS/NZS 60335.2.95 is the safety standard for power-operated
          doors, and it covers the force limits the opener must respect, the
          obstruction-detection behaviour, and the safety-cable requirement on
          extension-spring systems. Every spring job we do is left compliant
          &mdash; safety cables fitted (or replaced if missing), opener force
          re-calibrated against the new spring tension, and obstruction
          reversal re-tested before we leave.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner" style="text-align: center;">
      <h2>Broken spring? Same-day call-out across Cranbourne.</h2>
      <p style="max-width: 50rem; margin: 1rem auto;">
